declarations.comments: `get annoy i` returns `i`-th vector. Performs bounds check.
declarations.title: get

declarations.comments: Similar to `get` but no bounds checks are performed.
declarations.title: unsafeGet

declarations.comments: `length annoy` returns number of stored vectors
declarations.title: length

declarations.comments: `save annoy path` dumps annoy to the file. Boolean indicates succes or failure.
declarations.title: save

declarations.comments:
`unsafeLoad { size , metric } path` creates `STAnnoy` using `size` and `metric`, then loads annoy using `path`
Unsafe aspect is that it does not check loaded vector sizes against `size`
declarations.title: unsafeLoad

declarations.comments:
`nnsByItem a i n update`
Works like `nnsByVec`, but requires index instead of vector
declarations.title: nnsByItem

declarations.comments:
`nnsByItem_ a i n update`
Works like `nnsByVec_`, but requires index instead of vector
declarations.title: nnsByItem_

declarations.comments:
`nnsByVec a v n update`
Returns `n` closest items to the `v` vector. `update` is used to set **search_k** parameter.
`nnsByVec a v n id` to use default `searchK`
`nnsByVec a v n (_ { searchK = 123 })` to set `searchK`
declarations.title: nnsByVec

declarations.comments: Works like `nnsByVec` but also returns distances
declarations.title: nnsByVec_

declarations.comments:
`fromVectors options@{ trees , metric } vectors`
Creates new Annoy with `metric`, adds given vectors and executes `build` using `trees`.
declarations.title: fromVectors

declarations.comments: Similar to `fromVectors` but `trees` :: Int.
declarations.title: fromVectors_

declarations.comments:
`build { trees } m` executes `m` which creates Annoy and adds vectors, then builds it using `trees` (more info in original [annoy](https://github.com/spotify/annoy))
```purescript
a = build { trees: d1 } (do
  a <- new { size: d2 , metric: Manhattan }
  push (1.0 +> 2.0 +> empty) a
  push (3.0 +> 4.0 +> empty) a
  push (5.0 +> 6.0 +> empty) a
  pure a)
```
declarations.title: build

declarations.comments: Similar to `build` but `trees` argument is an Int, so return type is Maybe
declarations.title: build_

declarations.comments: `new { size , metric }` creates mutable annoy that stores vectors of `size` and uses given `metric`
declarations.title: new

declarations.comments: `push annoy v` adds vector `v` at index 'len' which is equal to the number of currently stored vectors
declarations.title: push

declarations.comments:
`Annoy s` where `s` is size of vectors.
Built/Immutable Annoy.
declarations.title: Annoy

declarations.comments:
`STAnnoy h s` where s is allowed size of vectors.
Similar to `STPrimAnnoy` but keeps track of vectors size `s`.
declarations.title: STAnnoy

declarations.comments: `STPrimAnnoy h` foreign type used in Unsafe module.
declarations.title: STPrimAnnoy

declarations.comments:
`unsafeNew f metric`
Creates new `STPrimAnnoy` that stores vector of `f` dimensions with `metric`. Does not validate input.
declarations.title: unsafeNew

declarations.comments: Inserts vector at given index. No checks for: not frozen `STPrimAnnoy`, matching dimension, negative index.
declarations.title: unsafeAddItem

declarations.comments: Builds a forest of given number of trees. After calling, no more items can be added.
declarations.title: unsafeBuild

declarations.comments: Saves the index to disk.
declarations.title: save

declarations.comments: Loads an index from disk.
declarations.title: unsafeLoad

declarations.comments: Returns vector under given index. No bounds checks are performed.
declarations.title: unsafeGetItem

declarations.comments:
`unsafeGetNNsByItem a i n search_k`
Returns `n` closest items to the `i`-th vector. No bounds checks are performed.
declarations.title: unsafeGetNNsByItem

declarations.comments: Like `unsafeGetNNsByItem` but returns also distances
declarations.title: unsafeGetNNsByItem_

declarations.comments:
`unsafeGetNNsByVector a v n search_k`
Like above but query by vector v instead of index.
declarations.title: unsafeGetNNsByVector

declarations.comments: Like `unsafeGetNNsByVector` but returns also distances
declarations.title: unsafeGetNNsByVector_

declarations.comments: Returns number of (allocated!) elements in Annoy.
declarations.title: getNItems

declarations.comments: Returns the distance between items at positions `i` and `j`. No bounds checks are performed.
declarations.title: unsafeGetDistance
